==Clinically used drugs==
===Approved drugs===
* [[Bupropion/dextromethorphan]] (DXM/BUP; Auvelity) – sigma σ<sub>1</sub> receptor agonist, serotonin reuptake inhibitor, norepinephrine and dopamine reuptake inhibitor, nicotinic acetylcholine receptor negative allosteric modulator, ionotropic glutamate NMDA receptor antagonist, other actions, CYP2D6 inhibitor, and dissociative hallucinogen combination – major depressive disorder – Axsome Therapeutics <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://adisinsight.springer.com/drugs/800044221|title=Bupropion/dextromethorphan - Axsome Therapeutics - AdisInsight|website=adisinsight.springer.com}}</ref>
* [[Esketamine]] ((''S'')-ketamine; Spravato) – ionotropic glutamate NMDA receptor antagonist and dissociative hallucinogen – major depressive disorder – Johnson & Johnson <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://adisinsight.springer.com/drugs/800037644|title=Esketamine - Johnson & Johnson - AdisInsight|website=adisinsight.springer.com}}</ref>

===Off-label drugs===
* [[Ketamine]] – ionotropic glutamate NMDA receptor antagonist and dissociative hallucinogen – major depressive disorder, other depressive disorders, and other conditions <ref name="FeeneyPapakostas2023">{{cite journal | vauthors = Feeney A, Papakostas GI | title = Pharmacotherapy: Ketamine and Esketamine | journal = Psychiatr Clin North Am | volume = 46 | issue = 2 | pages = 277–290 | date = June 2023 | pmid = 37149345 | doi = 10.1016/j.psc.2023.02.003 | url = | doi-access = free }}</ref>

===Discontinued drugs===
* [[α-Methyltryptamine]] (Indopan; αMT; AMT) – serotonin–norepinephrine–dopamine releasing agent, non-selective serotonin receptor agonist, weak monoamine oxidase inhibitor, entactogen, and psychedelic hallucinogen – depression – unknown (marketed in the Soviet Union) <ref name="Barceloux2012">{{cite book | last=Barceloux | first=Donald G. | chapter=Tryptamine Designer Drugs | title=Medical Toxicology of Drug Abuse: Synthesized Chemicals and Psychoactive Plants | publisher=Wiley | date=9 March 2012 | isbn=978-0-471-72760-6 | doi=10.1002/9781118105955.ch11 | pages=193–199 | quote=During the early 1960s, α-ethyltryptamine [(AET)] (Monase®, Upjohn Company) was marketed in the United States as an antidepressant and stimulant, but the drug was removed shortly after introduction because of the occurrence of serious blood disorders. [...] [α-Methyltryptamine (AMT)] (Indopan) was marketed in the Soviet Union during the 1960s as an antidepressant. }}</ref>
* [[Etryptamine]] (Monase; α-ethyltryptamine; αET; AET) – serotonin–norepinephrine–dopamine releasing agent, serotonin receptor agonist, weak monoamine oxidase inhibitor, and entactogen – depression – Upjohn <ref name="GlennonDukat2023">{{cite journal | vauthors = Glennon RA, Dukat MG | title = α-Ethyltryptamine: A Ratiocinatory Review of a Forgotten Antidepressant | journal = ACS Pharmacol Transl Sci | volume = 6 | issue = 12 | pages = 1780–1789 | date = December 2023 | pmid = 38093842 | pmc = 10714429 | doi = 10.1021/acsptsci.3c00139 | url = }}</ref><ref name="Barceloux2012" />
* ''[[Tabernanthe|Tabernanthe spp.]]'' [[extract]]s (containing [[ibogaine]]) (Lambarène, Iperton) – various actions and stimulant – fatigue, asthenia, depression, illness recovery <ref name="MaciulaitisKontrimaviciuteBressolle2008">{{cite journal | vauthors = Maciulaitis R, Kontrimaviciute V, Bressolle FM, Briedis V | title = Ibogaine, an anti-addictive drug: pharmacology and time to go further in development. A narrative review | journal = Hum Exp Toxicol | volume = 27 | issue = 3 | pages = 181–194 | date = March 2008 | pmid = 18650249 | doi = 10.1177/0960327107087802 | bibcode = 2008HETox..27..181M | url = }}</ref><ref name="Mash2023">{{cite journal | vauthors = Mash DC | title = IUPHAR - invited review - Ibogaine - A legacy within the current renaissance of psychedelic therapy | journal = Pharmacol Res | volume = 190 | issue = | article-number = 106620 | date = April 2023 | pmid = 36907284 | doi = 10.1016/j.phrs.2022.106620 | url = | doi-access = free }}</ref>

